Imagination, on the other hand, expands and enlarges the mental sphere in every direction—above, below, around-encompassing it with an aery region, extending far beyond the confines of the known. Into this region the psyche penetrates, supported by conjecture, probability, hypothesis—the “ if‚'' ‘³ sup· pose,’' “ perhaps ’'-and discovers in the far distance truths not revealed to those who, too cautious for such adventurous speculation, keep within the narrow‚ but safe, limits of proved and certain fact. And in this boundless aerial country it forms out of materials taken from reality, its ideal conceptions—of beauty more perfect, of grandeur more imposing, of events more exciting, of goodness and pleasure more abounding with joy or more full of promise than any· thing offered to its eye by actual fact. And it isa characteristic of a mind of the class which we are now describing, that, not content with its own con· ‚ ceptions, it invites and hospitably entertains those proceeding frorn other minds ; hailing their advent and meeting thern on their way, or even penetrating into the region in which they were engendered, and seizing them before fully formed.

And in proportion to the sensibility and vigour of the conceiving mind is the vividness and power of the conception.
